1. Where is the RISC-V program located?

The RISC-V program is located in the samples directory of the vsd-riscv2 repository (e.g., hello.c, sum1ton.c).
In FPGA labs, firmware is also present in basicRISCV/Firmware.

2. How is the program compiled and loaded into memory?

The program is compiled using the RISC-V GCC toolchain (riscv64-unknown-elf-gcc).
It generates an ELF or HEX file.
In FPGA flow, this compiled program is converted into a memory initialization file (firmware.hex) which is loaded into instruction memory during synthesis/simulation.

3. How does the RISC-V core access memory and memory-mapped IO?

The RISC-V core accesses memory using address-based read/write operations.
Memory and peripherals are mapped into the same address space (memory-mapped IO).
Specific addresses correspond to hardware modules (like UART), allowing the CPU to interact with them via load/store instructions.

4. Where would a new FPGA IP block integrate?

A new FPGA IP block would be integrated into the system bus or memory map.
It would be assigned a unique address range so the RISC-V core can access it like memory-mapped IO.
Integration happens at RTL level alongside existing modules like memory and peripherals.
